        "timestamp": "2017-09-20 13:49:47.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe patch set includes a submodule version update, how is the merge of of policy/engine change (and automatic submodule reference update in the doc project submodules) coordinated with the update in this patch set?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "643d6698797703e750739a6894ace16b513515a5",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1755,
          "name": "Spencer Seidel",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jsseidel@fastmail.com",
          "username": "jsseidel"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-20 14:19:17.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWhen you make changes to a submodule, you can commit and review those changes as normal. When you back out into the \"superproject\" and do a 'git status', git says there are changes in the submodule. I added the submodule to the commit, which was probably not the right thing to do. Should I abandon and try again w/o adding submodule changes?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "952477a8a70a453191b040d0e645f66e2927217d",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 19,
          "name": "Rich Bennett",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "r.njengineer@gmail.com",
          "username": "rb2745"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-20 14:33:01.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJust drop the policy engine reference from the patch set, you can do this in gerrit ui, I think this will resolve the conflict and the change(s) in policy engine are being tracked automatically by git",
        "patchset_number": 1
